# {{lb|en|grammar}} A pronoun which expresses possession.
#* '''1878''', Geo. F. Holmes, ''A Grammar of the English Language'', p 66:
#*: The '''possessive pronouns''' are, ''my, thy, his, her, its, our, your, their, own''.

====Usage notes====
* Words like {{m|en|my}} or {{m|en|their}}, which modify nouns and cannot stand on their own, are also commonly referred to as "possessive pronouns" (because of their relationship to the [[personal pronoun]]s). These are also called {{m|en|possessive determiner|possessive determiners}} or {{m|en|possessive adjective|possessive adjectives}}, however, as they are not pronouns in the strict sense.

